metadata.author: Paul Graham
metadata.title: Putting Ideas Into Words
metadata.sentence: Writing about something, even something you know well, usually shows you that you didn't know it as well as you thought

metadata.author: Paul Graham
metadata.title: Putting Ideas Into Words
metadata.sentence: Putting ideas into words is a severe test

metadata.author: Paul Graham
metadata.title: Putting Ideas Into Words
metadata.sentence: The first words you choose are usually wrong; you have to rewrite sentences over and over to get them exactly right

metadata.author: Paul Graham
metadata.title: Putting Ideas Into Words
metadata.sentence: And your ideas won't just be imprecise, but incomplete too

metadata.author: Paul Graham
metadata.title: Putting Ideas Into Words
metadata.sentence: Half the ideas that end up in an essay will be ones you thought of while you were writing it

metadata.author: Paul Graham
metadata.title: Putting Ideas Into Words
metadata.sentence: Indeed, that's why I write them

metadata.author: Paul Graham
metadata.title: Putting Ideas Into Words
metadata.sentence: Once you publish something, the convention is that whatever you wrote was what you thought before you wrote it

metadata.author: Paul Graham
metadata.title: Putting Ideas Into Words
metadata.sentence: These were your ideas, and now you've expressed them

metadata.author: Paul Graham
metadata.title: Putting Ideas Into Words
metadata.sentence: But you know this isn't true

metadata.author: Paul Graham
metadata.title: Putting Ideas Into Words
metadata.sentence: You know that putting your ideas into words changed them

metadata.author: Paul Graham
metadata.title: Putting Ideas Into Words
metadata.sentence: And not just the ideas you published

metadata.author: Paul Graham
metadata.title: Putting Ideas Into Words
metadata.sentence: Presumably there were others that turned out to be too broken to fix, and those you discarded instead

metadata.author: Paul Graham
metadata.title: Putting Ideas Into Words
metadata.sentence: It's not just having to commit your ideas to specific words that makes writing so exacting

metadata.author: Paul Graham
metadata.title: Putting Ideas Into Words
metadata.sentence: The real test is reading what you've written

metadata.author: Paul Graham
metadata.title: Putting Ideas Into Words
metadata.sentence: You have to pretend to be a neutral reader who knows nothing of what's in your head, only what you wrote

metadata.author: Paul Graham
metadata.title: Putting Ideas Into Words
metadata.sentence: When he reads what you wrote, does it seem correct? Does it seem complete? If you make an effort, you can read your writing as if you were a complete stranger, and when you do the news is usually bad

metadata.author: Paul Graham
metadata.title: Putting Ideas Into Words
metadata.sentence: It takes me many cycles before I can get an essay past the stranger

metadata.author: Paul Graham
metadata.title: Putting Ideas Into Words
metadata.sentence: But the stranger is rational, so you always can, if you ask him what he needs

metadata.author: Paul Graham
metadata.title: Putting Ideas Into Words
metadata.sentence: If he's not satisfied because you failed to mention x or didn't qualify some sentence sufficiently, then you mention x or add more qualifications

metadata.author: Paul Graham
metadata.title: Putting Ideas Into Words
metadata.sentence: Happy now? It may cost you some nice sentences, but you have to resign yourself to that

metadata.author: Paul Graham
metadata.title: Putting Ideas Into Words
metadata.sentence: You just have to make them as good as you can and still satisfy the stranger

metadata.author: Paul Graham
metadata.title: Putting Ideas Into Words
metadata.sentence: This much, I assume, won't be that controversial

metadata.author: Paul Graham
metadata.title: Putting Ideas Into Words
metadata.sentence: I think it will accord with the experience of anyone who has tried to write about anything nontrivial

metadata.author: Paul Graham
metadata.title: Putting Ideas Into Words
metadata.sentence: There may exist people whose thoughts are so perfectly formed that they just flow straight into words

metadata.author: Paul Graham
metadata.title: Putting Ideas Into Words
metadata.sentence: But I've never known anyone who could do this, and if I met someone who said they could, it would seem evidence of their limitations rather than their ability

metadata.author: Paul Graham
metadata.title: Putting Ideas Into Words
metadata.sentence: Indeed, this is a trope in movies: the guy who claims to have a plan for doing some difficult thing, and who when questioned further, taps his head and says "It's all up here

metadata.author: Paul Graham
metadata.title: Putting Ideas Into Words
metadata.sentence: " Everyone watching the movie knows what that means

metadata.author: Paul Graham
metadata.title: Putting Ideas Into Words
metadata.sentence: At best the plan is vague and incomplete

metadata.author: Paul Graham
metadata.title: Putting Ideas Into Words
metadata.sentence: Very likely there's some undiscovered flaw that invalidates it completely

metadata.author: Paul Graham
metadata.title: Putting Ideas Into Words
metadata.sentence: At best it's a plan for a plan

metadata.author: Paul Graham
metadata.title: Putting Ideas Into Words
metadata.sentence: In precisely defined domains it's possible to form complete ideas in your head

metadata.author: Paul Graham
metadata.title: Putting Ideas Into Words
metadata.sentence: People can play chess in their heads, for example

metadata.author: Paul Graham
metadata.title: Putting Ideas Into Words
metadata.sentence: And mathematicians can do some amount of math in their heads, though they don't seem to feel sure of a proof over a certain length till they write it down

metadata.author: Paul Graham
metadata.title: Putting Ideas Into Words
metadata.sentence: But this only seems possible with ideas you can express in a formal language

metadata.author: Paul Graham
metadata.title: Putting Ideas Into Words
metadata.sentence: [1] Arguably what such people are doing is putting ideas into words in their heads

metadata.author: Paul Graham
metadata.title: Putting Ideas Into Words
metadata.sentence: I can to some extent write essays in my head

metadata.author: Paul Graham
metadata.title: Putting Ideas Into Words
metadata.sentence: I'll sometimes think of a paragraph while walking or lying in bed that survives nearly unchanged in the final version

metadata.author: Paul Graham
metadata.title: Putting Ideas Into Words
metadata.sentence: But really I'm writing when I do this

metadata.author: Paul Graham
metadata.title: Putting Ideas Into Words
metadata.sentence: I'm doing the mental part of writing; my fingers just aren't moving as I do it

metadata.author: Paul Graham
metadata.title: Putting Ideas Into Words
metadata.sentence:
[2]

You can know a great deal about something without writing about it

metadata.author: Paul Graham
metadata.title: Putting Ideas Into Words
metadata.sentence: Can you ever know so much that you wouldn't learn more from trying to explain what you know? I don't think so

metadata.author: Paul Graham
metadata.title: Putting Ideas Into Words
metadata.sentence: I've written about at least two subjects I know well — Lisp hacking and startups — and in both cases I learned a lot from writing about them

metadata.author: Paul Graham
metadata.title: Putting Ideas Into Words
metadata.sentence: In both cases there were things I didn't consciously realize till I had to explain them

metadata.author: Paul Graham
metadata.title: Putting Ideas Into Words
metadata.sentence: And I don't think my experience was anomalous

metadata.author: Paul Graham
metadata.title: Putting Ideas Into Words
metadata.sentence: A great deal of knowledge is unconscious, and experts have if anything a higher proportion of unconscious knowledge than beginners

metadata.author: Paul Graham
metadata.title: Putting Ideas Into Words
metadata.sentence: I'm not saying that writing is the best way to explore all ideas

metadata.author: Paul Graham
metadata.title: Putting Ideas Into Words
metadata.sentence: If you have ideas about architecture, presumably the best way to explore them is to build actual buildings

metadata.author: Paul Graham
metadata.title: Putting Ideas Into Words
metadata.sentence: What I'm saying is that however much you learn from exploring ideas in other ways, you'll still learn new things from writing about them

metadata.author: Paul Graham
metadata.title: Putting Ideas Into Words
metadata.sentence: Putting ideas into words doesn't have to mean writing, of course

metadata.author: Paul Graham
metadata.title: Putting Ideas Into Words
metadata.sentence: You can also do it the old way, by talking

metadata.author: Paul Graham
metadata.title: Putting Ideas Into Words
metadata.sentence: But in my experience, writing is the stricter test

metadata.author: Paul Graham
metadata.title: Putting Ideas Into Words
metadata.sentence: You have to commit to a single, optimal sequence of words

metadata.author: Paul Graham
metadata.title: Putting Ideas Into Words
metadata.sentence: Less can go unsaid when you don't have tone of voice to carry meaning

metadata.author: Paul Graham
metadata.title: Putting Ideas Into Words
metadata.sentence: And you can focus in a way that would seem excessive in conversation

metadata.author: Paul Graham
metadata.title: Putting Ideas Into Words
metadata.sentence: I'll often spend 2 weeks on an essay and reread drafts 50 times

metadata.author: Paul Graham
metadata.title: Putting Ideas Into Words
metadata.sentence: If you did that in conversation it would seem evidence of some kind of mental disorder

metadata.author: Paul Graham
metadata.title: Putting Ideas Into Words
metadata.sentence: If you're lazy, of course, writing and talking are equally useless

metadata.author: Paul Graham
metadata.title: Putting Ideas Into Words
metadata.sentence: But if you want to push yourself to get things right, writing is the steeper hill

metadata.author: Paul Graham
metadata.title: Putting Ideas Into Words
metadata.sentence:
[3]

The reason I've spent so long establishing this rather obvious point is that it leads to another that many people will find shocking

metadata.author: Paul Graham
metadata.title: Putting Ideas Into Words
metadata.sentence: If writing down your ideas always makes them more precise and more complete, then no one who hasn't written about a topic has fully formed ideas about it

metadata.author: Paul Graham
metadata.title: Putting Ideas Into Words
metadata.sentence: And someone who never writes has no fully formed ideas about anything nontrivial

metadata.author: Paul Graham
metadata.title: Putting Ideas Into Words
metadata.sentence: It feels to them as if they do, especially if they're not in the habit of critically examining their own thinking

metadata.author: Paul Graham
metadata.title: Putting Ideas Into Words
metadata.sentence: Ideas can feel complete

metadata.author: Paul Graham
metadata.title: Putting Ideas Into Words
metadata.sentence: It's only when you try to put them into words that you discover they're not

metadata.author: Paul Graham
metadata.title: Putting Ideas Into Words
metadata.sentence: So if you never subject your ideas to that test, you'll not only never have fully formed ideas, but also never realize it

metadata.author: Paul Graham
metadata.title: Putting Ideas Into Words
metadata.sentence: Putting ideas into words is certainly no guarantee that they'll be right

metadata.author: Paul Graham
metadata.title: Putting Ideas Into Words
metadata.sentence: Far from it

metadata.author: Paul Graham
metadata.title: Putting Ideas Into Words
metadata.sentence: But though it's not a sufficient condition, it is a necessary one
